window.CERTHUB.searchIndex = [{"id":"gh-300/01-introduction/what-is-github-copilot","title":"What is GitHub Copilot","module":"Module 1 · Introduction","url":"gh-300/01-introduction/what-is-github-copilot","text":"GitHub Copilot is an AI pair programmer that helps you write, understand, and maintain code faster. It integrates directly into the editor and developer workflow — offering inline code completions, a conversational chat assistant, multi-file edits, autonomous agent tasks, terminal help, and pull-request assistance. For an experienced engineer, the mental model that matters is this: Copilot is a context-driven suggestion engine, not a search engine and not a compiler. It predicts likely code and prose from the context you give it, and you remain the accountable author and reviewer of everything it produces. Where Copilot fits in your workflow Copilot spans the full software development lifecycle rather than a single task: Authoring — inline completions and Copilot Chat while writing new code. Understanding — explaining unfamiliar code, dependencies, or stack traces. Changing — edit mode and agent mode for multi-file refactors and features. Reviewing — PR summaries and code review suggestions. Operating — CLI command help, test generation, and documentation. ℹ Note Copilot is available across popular surfaces: Visual Studio, VS Code, the JetBrains IDEs, Visual Studio for Mac (limited), the GitHub CLI, GitHub Mobile, and github.com . The exact feature set can differ by surface and by plan. What Copilot is good at Boilerplate and repetitive patterns (DTOs, mappers, CRUD scaffolding). Idiomatic usage of well-known frameworks (EF Core, Angular, xUnit). Explaining and summarising existing code. Drafting unit tests and documentation. Translating intent expressed in comments or chat","headings":["Where Copilot fits in your workflow","What Copilot is good at","What Copilot is not","A quick .NET example"]},{"id":"gh-300/01-introduction/ai-assistants-and-history","title":"AI coding assistants & history","module":"Module 1 · Introduction","url":"gh-300/01-introduction/ai-assistants-and-history","text":"Understanding where Copilot came from helps you reason about its strengths and limits — and a few historical facts show up as exam context. A short timeline 2021 — GitHub Copilot launches as a technical preview, powered by OpenAI Codex, offering inline completions in the editor. 2022 — General availability for individuals; the AI pair programmer positioning is established. 2023 — Copilot Chat arrives, adding a conversational interface; Copilot for Business brings organization-level management and policy controls. Later, Copilot Enterprise adds deeper GitHub-platform integration. 2024 onward — Expansion into edit mode , agent mode , model choice, richer context (workspace, repository indexing, knowledge bases), and integration into PRs, the CLI, and mobile. ℹ Note You do not need to memorise exact release dates for the exam. You should know the progression of capability — completions → chat → edits → agents — and that Business/Enterprise plans add management, policy, and platform features on top of the individual experience. From autocomplete to AI assistance Traditional IDE autocomplete (IntelliSense) is deterministic: it lists members and symbols that are valid at the cursor based on static analysis. It cannot invent a whole method or reason about intent. AI assistants like Copilot are generative and probabilistic . They predict the most likely continuation given the surrounding context and a large language model trained on vast amounts of public code and text. This is why they can scaffold an entire function from a comment — and also why they can produce confident but inc","headings":["A short timeline","From autocomplete to AI assistance","Why this matters for the exam"]},{"id":"gh-300/01-introduction/how-copilot-works","title":"How Copilot works","module":"Module 1 · Introduction","url":"gh-300/01-introduction/how-copilot-works","text":"At a high level, Copilot turns your context into a prompt , sends it to a large language model (LLM) , and streams back a suggestion that you accept, edit, or reject. Knowing the pipeline explains why context matters so much and why output varies. The suggestion pipeline Context gathering. Copilot collects signals from your environment: the current file, the code around your cursor (before and after), other open tabs/files, the file name and language, and — depending on surface and plan — related files, symbols, and repository content. Prompt assembly. These signals are packaged into a prompt within a bounded context window (a token limit). Not everything can fit, so relevance and proximity matter. Model inference. The LLM predicts the most likely continuation or answer. Post-processing filtering. Results pass through safety systems, including a filter that can block suggestions matching public code, and vulnerability-pattern filtering. Presentation. You see a completion (ghost text), a chat response, or proposed edits. Nothing is applied without your action. ℹ Note The context window is finite. If the relevant code is far away, in a closed file, or buried under noise, it may not influence the suggestion. This is the mechanical reason context engineering works. What counts as context Code immediately before and after the cursor (Copilot uses both). Open files / tabs in the editor (neighboring context). File name, language, and project signals. Comments and existing patterns in the file. On richer surfaces/plans: workspace context , repository indexing , chat participants li","headings":["The suggestion pipeline","What counts as context","Why suggestions vary","Content exclusions and filtering"]},{"id":"gh-300/01-introduction/exam-overview","title":"Exam overview & objectives","module":"Module 1 · Introduction","url":"gh-300/01-introduction/exam-overview","text":"The GH-300: GitHub Copilot certification validates that you can use Copilot effectively and responsibly across the development lifecycle, and that you understand its plans, administration, and Responsible-AI considerations. Format at a glance Item Detail Exam code GH-300 Style Multiple choice / multiple response Duration 100 minutes Delivery Pearson VUE test center or online proctored Price $99 USD Validity 24 months Audience Developers and administrators using GitHub Copilot ℹ Note GitHub publishes two overlapping views of the objectives: the exam registration outline (seven domains with fixed percentages) and the Microsoft Learn study guide (six skill groups with ranges, updated for the January 2026 exam revision). This portal uses a reconciled hybrid : it keeps testing as its own track while raising the Responsible-AI weighting to match the study guide's 15–20% range. Always reconfirm the current objectives on the official pages before your exam. The passing score is 700 (of 1000). Objective domains This portal maps to seven domains with reconciled weightings: # Domain Weight 1 Responsible AI — risks, limitations, ethics, and validating AI output 17% 2 GitHub Copilot plans and features — Free, Pro, Business, Enterprise; features across surfaces (largest domain) 27% 3 How GitHub Copilot works and handles data — the suggestion lifecycle, context building, proxy filtering, and data flow 12% 4 Prompt crafting and prompt engineering — structure, zero/few-shot, and best practices 12% 5 Developer use cases for AI — code generation, refactoring, docs, and modernization across th","headings":["Format at a glance","Objective domains","How to use this portal to prepare","Study checklist"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/inline-completion","title":"Inline code completion","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/inline-completion","text":"Inline completion is Copilot's original and most-used surface: as you type, it offers ghost text suggestions ranging from the rest of a line to entire functions. You accept with Tab , dismiss with Esc , or cycle alternatives. How it works Copilot continuously assembles context from the code around your cursor (before and after), open files, and the file's language, then predicts the most likely continuation. Suggestions update as the context changes, so small edits or an added comment can produce a very different (often better) result. Accept : Tab Dismiss : Esc Next / previous alternative : Alt + ] / Alt + [ (VS Code) Accept word-by-word : Ctrl + → Driving completions with intent The single biggest lever is a clear, specific comment or signature immediately before the cursor. Best practices ★ Best Practice Write the method signature and a one-line intent comment first, then let Copilot fill the body. Keep relevant type definitions open in a tab so the model can see them. Accept in small chunks (word/line) when precision matters, rather than accepting a whole block blindly. Immediately read the accepted code — treat acceptance as the start of review, not the end. Limitations Suggestions are probabilistic — the same spot can yield different results. The model can invent APIs, packages, or parameters that don't exist ( hallucination ). It has no guaranteed view of code outside the context window. It reflects patterns in its training data, which may be outdated or insecure. Common mistakes ⚠ Common Mistake Accepting long completions without reading them ( Tab-tab-ship ). Assum","headings":["How it works","Driving completions with intent","Best practices","Limitations","Common mistakes","Enterprise considerations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/copilot-chat","title":"Copilot Chat","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/copilot-chat","text":"Copilot Chat is a conversational assistant embedded in the IDE and on github.com . Use it to explain code, propose changes, generate tests, fix errors, and answer questions — with awareness of your current file, selection, or wider workspace. How it works Chat combines your natural-language message with contextual signals (the active file, your selection, referenced files, and — depending on surface — the workspace or repository). It responds conversationally and can propose code you apply into the editor. Slash commands, participants, and variables These shortcuts steer chat toward the right task and context (availability varies by IDE): Type Example Purpose Slash command /explain , /fix , /tests , /doc , /optimize Invoke a common task Chat participant @workspace , @terminal , @vscode Scope context to a domain Context variable #file , #selection , #editor Attach specific context Inline chat vs chat view Inline chat works at the cursor for quick, in-place edits and questions. Chat view/panel is better for longer, multi-turn conversations and exploration. Best practices ★ Best Practice Be specific about the framework, version, and constraints ( Angular 18 standalone component with signals , .NET 8 minimal API ). Attach the right context with #file / #selection or @workspace instead of pasting large blocks. Iterate: refine the request based on the answer rather than starting over. Ask Copilot to explain trade-offs , not just produce code. Limitations Chat can still hallucinate APIs or give outdated guidance — verify against docs. Without the right context attached, answers ar","headings":["How it works","Slash commands, participants, and variables","Inline chat vs chat view","Best practices","Limitations","Enterprise considerations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/edit-and-agent-mode","title":"Edit mode & Agent mode","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/edit-and-agent-mode","text":"Beyond single completions and chat, Copilot offers two higher-order modes for changing code across files: edit mode (you direct, Copilot proposes coordinated edits) and agent mode (Copilot plans and executes a multi-step task more autonomously). Edit mode In edit mode you select a set of files as the working set, describe the change, and Copilot proposes edits across those files as a reviewable diff. You accept or discard changes hunk by hunk. You stay in control of the file set and the intent. Ideal for focused, cross-cutting changes: renaming a concept, threading a new parameter, applying a pattern consistently. Agent mode In agent mode, Copilot works more autonomously toward a goal: it can explore the codebase, plan steps, make edits across many files, run tools/terminal commands or tests where supported, and iterate on failures — pausing for your review and approval. Best for larger, multi-step tasks where the plan isn't fully known up front. You review the plan and the resulting changes; you approve actions. Choosing a mode Need Use One suggestion while typing Inline completion Explain / ask / quick local fix Chat (incl. inline chat) Coordinated edits across a known set of files Edit mode Multi-step task, exploration, run tests iterate Agent mode Best practices ★ Best Practice Keep the working set tight in edit mode — fewer, relevant files produce cleaner diffs. For agent mode, state the goal and constraints clearly, and review the plan before approving broad changes. Commit or stash first so you can diff and roll back easily. Review every hunk; run the build and tests","headings":["Edit mode","Agent mode","Choosing a mode","Best practices","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/plan-mode","title":"Plan Mode","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/plan-mode","text":"Plan Mode is a Copilot working mode that focuses on thinking before doing . Instead of immediately editing code, Copilot first produces a structured, reviewable plan — the steps, files, and approach it intends to take — which you refine and approve before any changes are made. Why Plan Mode exists Agent mode is powerful but can jump straight into edits. For larger or riskier tasks, you often want to agree on the approach first. Plan Mode separates planning from execution : You describe the goal. Copilot proposes a step-by-step plan (what it will change and why). You edit, reorder, or remove steps. You approve, and execution proceeds (typically handed to agent mode). When to use it Scenario Mode One suggestion while typing Inline completion Quick local change across known files Edit mode Just do it multi-step task Agent mode Complex/unfamiliar task where the approach matters Plan Mode Plan Mode shines for migrations, refactors that touch many layers, or work in an unfamiliar codebase where you want to validate the strategy before code changes. Example ★ Best Practice Treat the plan as a contract . Tighten scope, remove steps you'll do yourself, and add explicit constraints (naming, patterns, don't touch the public API ) before approving execution. ✓ Exam Tip On the exam, match the intent: review and agree the approach before any edits → Plan Mode ; autonomously carry out the steps → agent mode . ⚠ Common Mistake Approving a plan without reading it, then being surprised by broad changes. The plan is the cheapest place to catch a wrong approach — read it. Limitations A plan is","headings":["Why Plan Mode exists","When to use it","Example","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/agent-sessions-and-subagents","title":"Agent sessions & sub-agents","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/agent-sessions-and-subagents","text":"As agent mode has matured, GitHub Copilot organizes autonomous work into agent sessions and can delegate parts of a task to sub-agents . Understanding these helps you manage long-running work and keep context usage efficient. Agent sessions An agent session is a persistent, trackable unit of autonomous work. Rather than a single request/response, a session represents Copilot working toward a goal over multiple steps — planning, editing, running tools/tests, and iterating — while you monitor and approve. Sessions can be started, paused, resumed, and reviewed . Each session keeps its own working context and history of actions. You can run work locally (in the IDE) or delegate it to run asynchronously (for example, the Copilot coding agent working on an assigned issue and opening a pull request). Sub-agents For complex tasks, an agent can delegate a focused piece of work to a sub-agent . A sub-agent handles a narrower objective with its own scoped context , then returns a result to the parent agent. Why this matters: Context efficiency — the main session isn't polluted with all the detail of every subtask; each sub-agent works within a smaller, relevant context window. Separation of concerns — e.g., one sub-agent explores and summarizes the codebase while the parent focuses on implementing the change. Better results on large tasks — narrower scope reduces the chance the model loses track of the goal. Delegating tasks You can assign work to Copilot the way you'd assign it to a teammate — for example, assigning a GitHub issue to the Copilot coding agent. It works in a session, p","headings":["Agent sessions","Sub-agents","Delegating tasks","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/mcp-and-extensibility","title":"MCP & extensibility","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/mcp-and-extensibility","text":"The Model Context Protocol (MCP) is an open standard that lets AI tools like GitHub Copilot connect to external tools, data sources, and services in a consistent, secure way. MCP is how you extend what Copilot can see and do beyond your open files. What MCP is An MCP server exposes capabilities — tools (actions Copilot can call), resources (data it can read), and prompts — over a standard protocol. An MCP client (Copilot in your IDE or Copilot Chat) discovers and calls those capabilities. Open standard — any compliant server works with any compliant client. Tools — e.g., query this database , create a Jira ticket , search our docs . Resources — structured data the model can pull into context on demand. The GitHub MCP server is a first-party example: it exposes GitHub features (issues, PRs, repositories, actions) to your AI tools so Copilot can work with them directly. Why it matters Copilot's quality depends on context. MCP lets you ground Copilot in systems it otherwise couldn't reach — internal APIs, ticketing systems, databases, observability tools — turning it from a code-completion tool into an assistant that can act across your toolchain. Configuring and using MCP Add an MCP server (first-party like GitHub, or your own/team's). Authenticate it (tokens/OAuth) with least-privilege scopes. Use it from Copilot Chat — Copilot can call the server's tools as part of answering or acting. Troubleshoot connection/permission issues (server not starting, missing scopes, tool not appearing). ★ Best Practice Grant MCP servers the least privilege they need, prefer trusted/first-part","headings":["What MCP is","Why it matters","Configuring and using MCP","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/copilot-cli","title":"Copilot in the CLI","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/copilot-cli","text":"Copilot in the CLI brings assistance to the terminal through the GitHub CLI ( gh ). It helps you find the right command, explain an unfamiliar one, and translate natural language into shell, git , or gh commands — without leaving the terminal. How it works After installing the gh CLI and the Copilot extension, you ask in plain language and Copilot proposes a command with an explanation. You review it, then choose to run, copy, or revise — the command is never executed without your confirmation . Typical uses Recalling infrequent git operations (interactive rebase, reflog recovery). Building gh commands for PRs, issues, and workflows. Explaining a risky command before you run it. Composing shell one-liners for file and text processing. Best practices ★ Best Practice Always read the explanation and understand a command before running it — especially anything destructive ( rm , git reset --hard , force-push). Use explain to learn, not just suggest to act. Prefer non-destructive alternatives when offered. Limitations Suggested commands can be wrong or unsafe for your specific environment. Copilot doesn't know your machine's full state or side effects. It won't run commands for you automatically — and that's by design. ⚠ Common Mistake Blindly pasting and running a suggested destructive command. The confirmation step exists precisely so you can catch mistakes; don't treat it as a formality. ✓ Exam Tip Know that CLI assistance uses gh copilot suggest and gh copilot explain , requires confirmation before running, and is delivered as a gh extension.","headings":["How it works","Typical uses","Best practices","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/context-and-prompt-files","title":"Context & prompt files","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/context-and-prompt-files","text":"Copilot's output quality is bounded by the context it can see. This page covers how to supply context deliberately, and how prompt files let you package reusable, shareable prompts for repeatable tasks. Sources of context Cursor surroundings — code before and after the caret. Open editors / tabs — neighboring files inform suggestions. Explicit references — #file , #selection , #editor in chat. Workspace participant — @workspace lets chat reason over the project. Repository indexing / knowledge bases — broader, semantic context (plan-dependent). ℹ Note Because the context window is finite, relevance beats volume . Attaching the two files that matter usually beats dumping ten files or a giant selection. Prompt files Prompt files ( *.prompt.md ) let you save a reusable prompt — instructions plus references — as a file in the repo, so a task can be run consistently by anyone on the team. They're ideal for standardised generation tasks ( scaffold a CRUD controller following our conventions ). Best practices ★ Best Practice Open or reference the files that define the types you're working with. Use prompt files for tasks the team repeats, so results are consistent and reviewable. Keep prompts and references version-controlled — they evolve with the codebase. Remove noise (dead code, unrelated files) from the working context when generating. Limitations Context that isn't visible or referenced generally isn't used. Very large references can crowd out the important parts within the token budget. Prompt-file availability and syntax can vary by surface/version. ⚠ Common Mistake Expect","headings":["Sources of context","Prompt files","Best practices","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/custom-instructions","title":"Custom instructions","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/custom-instructions","text":"Custom instructions are always-on guidance that Copilot applies automatically to your requests, so you don't have to restate standing preferences in every prompt. They're the primary way to make Copilot follow team conventions consistently. Where they live Repository custom instructions — a .github/copilot-instructions.md file committed to the repo. It applies to Copilot Chat requests in that repository for everyone. Path-specific instructions — *.instructions.md files with an applyTo glob, so different rules apply to different parts of the codebase. Personal instructions — user-level preferences that travel with you across repositories (surface-dependent). What to put in them Language/framework versions and idioms. Naming, formatting, and architectural patterns. Testing framework and style. Security and logging rules (e.g., never hard-code secrets ). Things to avoid (deprecated APIs, banned packages). Best practices ★ Best Practice Keep instructions short, specific, and stable — they consume context on every request. Commit them so the whole team benefits and they evolve via PRs. Use path-specific files for monorepos with mixed stacks. State rules as imperatives ( use X , never do Y ). Limitations Instructions are guidance, not hard guarantees — Copilot can still deviate. Overly long instructions waste the context budget and dilute focus. They don't replace review, tests, or linting. ⚠ Common Mistake Writing a huge, vague instructions file ( write good, clean, secure code ). Non-specific guidance changes little. Prefer concrete, checkable rules. ✓ Exam Tip Contrast the thr","headings":["Where they live","What to put in them","Best practices","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/pull-requests-and-code-review","title":"Pull requests & code review","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/pull-requests-and-code-review","text":"Copilot extends into the collaboration stage of the lifecycle with pull-request summaries and AI code review , helping authors describe changes and reviewers catch issues faster. PR summaries On github.com , Copilot can generate a summary of the changes in a pull request — an overview and a walkthrough of modified files — which the author edits and keeps. This speeds up writing good PR descriptions and helps reviewers orient quickly. ℹ Note The author remains responsible for the final description. Treat the generated summary as a first draft to refine, not a finished record. Copilot code review Copilot can review a pull request and leave suggestions — flagging potential bugs, style issues, and improvements, sometimes with proposed code changes you can apply. You can request a review from Copilot much like requesting one from a teammate. Fast first pass that catches obvious issues before human reviewers spend time. Suggestions are advisory — humans approve and merge. Where each fits Task Feature Draft the PR description PR summary Get an automated first-pass review Copilot code review Approve and merge Human reviewer (always) Best practices ★ Best Practice Use Copilot review as an early gate , not a replacement for human review. Keep PRs small — Copilot (and humans) review focused changes better. Verify each suggested change; apply only what genuinely improves the code. Edit the generated summary to capture intent and risk , which the model can't fully infer. Limitations Copilot may miss domain-specific or architectural problems. It can produce false positives or superficial","headings":["PR summaries","Copilot code review","Where each fits","Best practices","Limitations","Enterprise considerations"]},{"id":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/tests-docs-and-refactoring","title":"Tests, docs, refactoring & debugging","module":"Module 2 · Copilot Fundamentals","url":"gh-300/02-fundamentals/tests-docs-and-refactoring","text":"Some of Copilot's highest-value everyday tasks are generating tests, writing documentation, refactoring safely, and helping debug. These map to the exam's developer use cases and testing domains. Test generation Copilot drafts unit tests from your code and intent — a strong fit for xUnit/NUnit in .NET and Jasmine/Jest in Angular. Ask for specific cases, not just write tests. ★ Best Practice Prompt for edge cases and failure modes explicitly (nulls, empty collections, boundaries, exceptions). Copilot happily writes the happy path; you must direct it to the risky paths. Documentation Copilot generates XML doc comments, README sections, and inline explanations. Refactoring Use chat or edit mode to restructure code while preserving behavior: extract methods, introduce patterns, modernise syntax (e.g., to C# 12 or Angular signals). ★ Best Practice Refactor behind tests . Generate/confirm tests first, refactor second, then re-run the suite. This turns does it still work? into an automatic check. Debugging Paste an error, stack trace, or failing test into chat and ask for likely causes and fixes. /fix targets the current problem in context. Limitations Generated tests may assert the current (possibly buggy) behavior rather than the correct behavior — you define correctness. Refactors can subtly change behavior; only tests catch that reliably. Debugging suggestions are hypotheses, not diagnoses. Common mistakes ⚠ Common Mistake Trusting generated tests as proof of correctness. Tests written from the same flawed assumptions can pass while the code is wrong. Refactoring without a tes","headings":["Test generation","Documentation","Refactoring","Debugging","Limitations","Common mistakes"]},{"id":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/prompting-principles","title":"Prompting principles","module":"Module 3 · Prompt Engineering","url":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/prompting-principles","text":"Prompt engineering is the practice of communicating intent so Copilot produces accurate, relevant output. For code, a few durable principles do most of the work. The four principles Be specific. State the language, framework/version, inputs, outputs, and constraints. Angular 18 standalone component using signals beats an Angular component. Give context. Open or reference the relevant types and examples so the model sees your domain, not a generic one. Show the shape. Provide a signature, an example input/output, or an existing pattern to imitate. Iterate. Treat the first response as a draft; refine with follow-ups rather than restarting. ≡ Example Vague: write a function to process orders Specific: Write a C# method decimal CalculateTotal(Order order) that sums Quantity * UnitPrice * (1 + TaxRate) per line, rounds to 2dp, and throws ArgumentException if any quantity is negative. Anatomy of a strong prompt Goal — what you want produced. Context — the relevant code/types (referenced, not pasted when possible). Constraints — versions, patterns, performance, security, style. Format — the exact output shape (a method, a test class, a diff). Good vs poor prompts Poor Better Fix this This throws NRE when order.Lines is null; guard it and add a test. Make it faster This LINQ runs per-row queries (N+1); rewrite to a single EF Core query. Write tests Write xUnit tests for empty, boundary, and negative-quantity cases. ★ Best Practice Front-load the most important constraint . If security or a specific API matters most, say so first — models weight early, explicit instructions heavily.","headings":["The four principles","Anatomy of a strong prompt","Good vs poor prompts"]},{"id":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/prompting-techniques","title":"Prompting techniques","module":"Module 3 · Prompt Engineering","url":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/prompting-techniques","text":"Beyond general principles, a handful of named techniques appear on the exam and are genuinely useful day to day. Zero-shot prompting You describe the task with no examples and let the model infer the pattern. Fast and often enough for common tasks. Few-shot prompting You provide one or more examples of the desired input/output so the model matches your exact style. Use when output shape or conventions matter. ℹ Note Zero-shot = no examples; one-shot = a single example; few-shot = a small number of examples. More/better examples generally improve adherence to your desired format. Chain-of-thought / step-by-step Ask the model to reason in steps or to plan before coding for complex tasks. Useful for multi-part logic and debugging. Role and persona framing Setting a role can focus the response ( Act as a security reviewer and identify injection risks in #selection ). Decomposition Break a big request into smaller prompts. Generate the interface, then the implementation, then the tests — reviewing each before moving on. Technique selection Situation Technique Common, well-known task Zero-shot Must match a specific style/format Few-shot Complex reasoning or multi-step logic Step-by-step / decomposition Focused perspective (security, perf) Role framing ★ Best Practice Combine techniques: a few-shot example plus an explicit constraint list plus decomposition yields the most controllable results on non-trivial tasks. ⚠ Common Mistake Using a single giant prompt for a large task and accepting the whole output. Decompose and review in stages to keep quality and reviewability high. ✓ E","headings":["Zero-shot prompting","Few-shot prompting","Chain-of-thought / step-by-step","Role and persona framing","Decomposition","Technique selection"]},{"id":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/context-engineering","title":"Context engineering","module":"Module 3 · Prompt Engineering","url":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/context-engineering","text":"If prompting is what you ask , context engineering is what you let Copilot see . Because the model works within a finite context window, curating context is often more impactful than wording. The context window Everything Copilot considers — your prompt, referenced files, surrounding code — must fit within a token budget. When it's full, less-relevant content is dropped. Your job is to make sure the right content is in view. Levers you control Open the defining files. Keep the types, interfaces, and one exemplar implementation visible. Reference precisely. Use #file , #selection , @workspace instead of pasting. Reduce noise. Close unrelated tabs; remove dead code from the active file. Provide an exemplar. One good example of your pattern steers everything after it. Use custom instructions for standing conventions so they don't crowd each prompt. ≡ Example Generating a repository class? Have IOrderRepository.cs , Order.cs , and an existing ProductRepository.cs open. Copilot will mirror your constructor injection, naming, and EF Core usage almost exactly. Relevance beats volume More context is not better. Ten loosely related files can bury the two that matter and push them out of the window. Curate for relevance and proximity . Repository-scale context On richer plans/surfaces, repository indexing and @workspace provide semantic search across the codebase, and knowledge bases (Enterprise) add curated docs. These extend context beyond open files — but curation still helps. Best practices ★ Best Practice Assemble a minimal, high-signal working set before generating. Lead with a","headings":["The context window","Levers you control","Relevance beats volume","Repository-scale context","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/iteration-and-templates","title":"Iteration & prompt templates","module":"Module 3 · Prompt Engineering","url":"gh-300/03-prompt-engineering/iteration-and-templates","text":"Great results rarely come from the first prompt. Iteration — and capturing what works as templates — turns one-off wins into repeatable quality. The refinement loop Draft a prompt with goal, context, and constraints. Generate and read the output critically. Diagnose the gap (missing edge case? wrong pattern? outdated API?). Refine the prompt or context and regenerate. Lock in the working prompt as a template or instruction. Each turn narrows toward the intended design without discarding progress. Prompt templates A template is a reusable prompt skeleton for a recurring task. Capture them where the team can reuse them — as prompt files ( *.prompt.md ) or in a shared prompt library. Reusable building blocks Constraint block — your standing rules (versions, patterns, security). Format block — the exact output shape you want. Context block — the standard files to reference for a task type. Best practices ★ Best Practice Keep a personal/team prompt library for high-value tasks (endpoints, tests, migrations). Version prompt files with the code so they evolve together. Refine the context as readily as the wording — often it's the real bottleneck. ⚠ Common Mistake Restarting from scratch when an answer is close. Iterating on the existing thread preserves useful context and converges faster. ✓ Exam Tip Recognise prompt templates / prompt files as a way to standardise and share effective prompts across a team — a governance and consistency win, not just a convenience.","headings":["The refinement loop","Prompt templates","Reusable building blocks","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/responsible-ai-overview","title":"Responsible AI overview","module":"Module 4 · Responsible AI","url":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/responsible-ai-overview","text":"Responsible AI is a core GH-300 domain. It covers the risks inherent in generative AI and the practices — above all, human oversight — that keep Copilot use safe, fair, and accountable. Key risks Hallucinations Copilot can produce output that is confident but wrong : nonexistent APIs, invented parameters, plausible-but-incorrect logic. This stems directly from its probabilistic, generative nature. Bias and fairness Because models learn from large public datasets, they can reflect biases present in that data — in naming, assumptions, examples, or comments. Outputs should be reviewed for fairness and inclusivity. Over-reliance / automation bias The tendency to trust automated output too readily. The more fluent the suggestion, the easier it is to skip scrutiny — which is exactly when errors slip through. Security and quality Generated code may contain vulnerabilities or poor practices learned from training data. It is not pre-verified for your context. The human-in-the-loop principle The unifying answer across this domain: the developer is accountable. Copilot assists; humans decide. Every suggestion must be reviewed, tested, and validated before it ships. ✓ Exam Tip When a Responsible-AI question offers an option involving human review, validation, or developer accountability, it is very often the correct answer. Copilot augments developers; it does not replace their judgement or responsibility. Practices that mitigate the risks Review everything Copilot produces before accepting or merging. Test generated code, including edge cases and security-sensitive paths. Scan for vul","headings":["Key risks","Hallucinations","Bias and fairness","Over-reliance / automation bias","Security and quality","The human-in-the-loop principle","Practices that mitigate the risks"]},{"id":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/security-and-privacy","title":"Security & privacy","module":"Module 4 · Responsible AI","url":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/security-and-privacy","text":"Copilot can accelerate secure development — and, if used carelessly, introduce risk. This page covers secure-coding responsibilities, prompt-injection awareness, and how Copilot handles your data. Generated code is not pre-vetted Suggestions can contain vulnerabilities learned from public code: injection flaws, weak crypto, missing authorization, hard-coded secrets. You own the security review. ★ Best Practice Keep the OWASP Top 10 in mind when reviewing generated code: injection, broken access control, cryptographic failures, SSRF, and friends. Route Copilot output through the same SAST, dependency, and secret scanning as any code. Don't leak secrets or sensitive data Never paste secrets, tokens, customer PII, or proprietary data into prompts unnecessarily. Use content exclusions to keep sensitive files out of Copilot's context. Read secrets from a vault (e.g., Azure Key Vault ), never hard-code them — and don't let a suggestion talk you into it. Prompt-injection awareness Prompt injection is when untrusted content (a file, web page, issue, or dependency) contains instructions that try to manipulate the AI's behavior. As Copilot gains context from more sources (agents, web, repos), treat external content as data, not commands , and review actions an agent proposes. ⚠ Common Mistake Assuming text pulled into context is trustworthy. Malicious instructions embedded in a document or repo can attempt to steer generation. Review agent actions and generated code regardless of source. How Copilot handles data (fundamentals) Business and Enterprise : prompts and suggestions are not","headings":["Generated code is not pre-vetted","Don't leak secrets or sensitive data","Prompt-injection awareness","How Copilot handles data (fundamentals)"]},{"id":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/ip-licensing-and-duplication","title":"IP, licensing & duplication","module":"Module 4 · Responsible AI","url":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/ip-licensing-and-duplication","text":"Intellectual-property questions are a recurring theme: who owns Copilot's output, what happens if a suggestion resembles public code, and how the duplication filter and IP indemnity fit in. Ownership of suggestions Copilot suggestions are generated for you to use, and you are responsible for the code you accept and ship. Because you're accountable for the final code, you must ensure it complies with your licensing and IP obligations — just as you would for code from any source. Matching public code (duplication) filter Copilot includes an optional filter that detects and blocks suggestions matching public code (roughly, ~150 characters of overlap with public repositories). Administrators (Business/Enterprise) or individuals can enable it. Enabled → suggestions that match public code are suppressed, reducing the chance of reproducing licensed code verbatim. Disabled → such suggestions may appear; you carry more review responsibility. ✓ Exam Tip Know that the duplication/matching filter blocks suggestions that match public code and is an admin/individual setting . If a scenario worries about reproducing licensed public code, enabling this filter is the mitigating control. IP indemnity For Copilot Business and Enterprise , GitHub offers an IP indemnification commitment for eligible use — covering certain third-party IP claims arising from Copilot suggestions — provided the duplication-detection filter is enabled. This is a plan-level benefit, not available on the free individual tier. ℹ Note Indemnity is conditional (e.g., filter enabled, following terms). The exam-relevant po","headings":["Ownership of suggestions","Matching public code (duplication) filter","IP indemnity","Licensing hygiene","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/validation-and-human-review","title":"Validation & human review","module":"Module 4 · Responsible AI","url":"gh-300/04-responsible-ai/validation-and-human-review","text":"Every Responsible-AI thread converges here: generated code must be validated by a human before it ships. This page turns that principle into a concrete workflow. Why validation is non-negotiable Output is probabilistic — plausible isn't correct. The model can't verify against your runtime, data, or requirements. Accountability stays with the developer and the team, not the tool. A validation workflow Read the suggestion fully — understand every line before accepting. Check intent — does it actually solve the requirement, including edge cases? Verify facts — do the APIs, packages, and parameters really exist? Test — run existing tests; add tests for new/edge behavior. Scan — SAST, dependency, and secret scanning. Review — human code review and approval before merge. ≡ Example Copilot suggests using a Enumerable.DistinctBy overload. Validation: confirm it exists for your target framework (.NET 6+), that it's the intended key, and add a test proving duplicates are removed by that key. Understanding before accepting If you can't explain what a suggestion does, you can't own it. I don't fully understand this, but it works is a red flag, not a shortcut. ★ Best Practice Make explainability a merge criterion: the author must be able to explain any Copilot-generated code as if they'd written it themselves. If they can't, it doesn't merge. Where extra scrutiny is required Security-sensitive code (auth, crypto, input handling). Financial or safety-critical logic. Data access and queries (correctness + injection). Anything touching PII or secrets. Best practices ★ Best Practice Apply t","headings":["Why validation is non-negotiable","A validation workflow","Understanding before accepting","Where extra scrutiny is required","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/05-enterprise/plans-and-comparison","title":"Plans & feature comparison","module":"Module 5 · Enterprise Features","url":"gh-300/05-enterprise/plans-and-comparison","text":"The plans domain is one of the largest on GH-300. You must be able to compare Copilot Free/Individual (Pro) , Copilot Business , and Copilot Enterprise , and match capabilities to each. The plans at a glance Capability Free / Pro (Individual) Business Enterprise Inline completions chat Yes (Free has limits) Yes Yes Managed via organization No Yes Yes Policy content exclusions Limited Yes Yes Code not used to train models Pro: yes Yes Yes IP indemnity (filter on) No Yes Yes Audit logs No Yes Yes Usage/engagement metrics No Yes Yes github.com deep integration No Limited Yes Knowledge bases No No Yes Copilot in PRs (summaries, etc.) Limited Varies Yes (fuller) ℹ Note Exact entitlements evolve. Focus on the shape : Individual = personal productivity; Business = org management, policy, security, indemnity; Enterprise = Business + deep platform integration and knowledge bases. Individual (Free Pro) For a single developer. Copilot Free offers a limited monthly allowance of completions/chat; Copilot Pro is the paid individual plan with full editor features. No organization-level administration, policy management, audit logs, or indemnity. Copilot Business Adds the organization layer: centralised license management, policy controls , content exclusions , audit logs , usage metrics, and IP indemnity (with the duplication filter enabled). Your code is not used to train the models. This is the baseline for most companies. Copilot Enterprise Everything in Business plus deep GitHub-platform integration : Copilot on github.com , repository-aware chat , knowledge bases built from your docs","headings":["The plans at a glance","Individual (Free Pro)","Copilot Business","Copilot Enterprise","Choosing a plan"]},{"id":"gh-300/05-enterprise/policies-and-governance","title":"Policies & governance","module":"Module 5 · Enterprise Features","url":"gh-300/05-enterprise/policies-and-governance","text":"With Business and Enterprise, administrators govern how Copilot is used across the organization. Knowing the available policy levers is essential for the enterprise-administration domain. Where administration happens Copilot is managed at the enterprise and organization levels via settings and policies. Admins assign seats/licenses , set policies , and monitor usage. Access can be granted to specific teams or organizations. Key policy controls Feature enablement — turn Copilot (and specific features like Chat, CLI, PR features) on or off for the org/enterprise. Matching-public-code filter (a.k.a. duplication detection) — require suggestions matching public code to be blocked. Content exclusions — specify files/paths/repos that Copilot must not use as context or send to the service. Seat management — assign/unassign licenses; control who has access. Data/telemetry settings — govern permitted data handling per plan. ℹ Note Content exclusions are configured by admins (repo or org level) and prevent matching files from being used as context — a primary tool for protecting sensitive code. Visibility: audit logs metrics Audit logs record Copilot-related administrative and access events for compliance. Usage/engagement metrics (and the Copilot metrics API) show adoption and activity, helping measure ROI and drive enablement. Governance model Effective governance combines: Policy — what's allowed (features, filters, exclusions). Access — who has seats and to which resources. Monitoring — audit logs and metrics for oversight. Guidance — custom instructions and internal standards for","headings":["Where administration happens","Key policy controls","Visibility: audit logs metrics","Governance model","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/05-enterprise/context-indexing-and-knowledge","title":"Context, indexing & knowledge bases","module":"Module 5 · Enterprise Features","url":"gh-300/05-enterprise/context-indexing-and-knowledge","text":"Enterprise plans extend Copilot's awareness beyond open files to the repository and to curated organizational knowledge . These features power more relevant, organization-specific answers. Repository indexing @workspace Copilot can build a semantic index of a repository so chat (via @workspace / repository-aware chat) can retrieve relevant code across the project — not just what's open. This improves questions like where is authentication handled? or how do we call the payments API? ℹ Note Indexing enables semantic retrieval across the codebase. It's what lets Copilot answer repo-wide questions rather than only reasoning over the current file. Knowledge bases (Enterprise) Copilot Enterprise lets organizations create knowledge bases from collections of Markdown documentation across repositories. Copilot Chat on github.com can then ground answers in that curated knowledge — internal standards, architecture docs, runbooks. Keeps answers aligned with your documented practices. Reduces reliance on generic public knowledge for internal questions. Curated and maintained by the organization. ✓ Exam Tip Knowledge bases are an Enterprise feature built from Markdown docs, used to ground Copilot Chat in organizational knowledge. If a scenario needs Copilot to answer using internal documentation, the answer is Enterprise knowledge bases. Layers of context (summary) Layer Scope Availability Cursor + open files Local All plans #file / #selection references Explicit All (chat) Repository indexing / @workspace Whole repo Broader on Enterprise-class surfaces Knowledge bases Curated org docs ","headings":["Repository indexing @workspace","Knowledge bases (Enterprise)","Layers of context (summary)","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/05-enterprise/spaces-and-spark","title":"Copilot Spaces & Spark","module":"Module 5 · Enterprise Features","url":"gh-300/05-enterprise/spaces-and-spark","text":"The January 2026 exam revision explicitly names two newer capabilities: Copilot Spaces (curated context for grounded answers) and GitHub Spark (build apps from natural language). Both extend Copilot beyond inline coding. Copilot Spaces A Copilot Space is a curated, reusable bundle of context — code, docs, notes, and other references — that you assemble so Copilot Chat gives grounded, higher-quality answers for a specific topic, project, or task. You choose what goes into the Space (repos, files, free-text instructions, links). Chat then reasons within that curated context , reducing generic or off-target answers. Spaces are shareable , so a team gets consistent, grounded responses instead of each person re-explaining the same background. Think of a Space as the briefing packet you'd hand a new teammate, made available to Copilot. ★ Best Practice Keep a Space focused and current . Curate the few references that matter for the topic rather than dumping everything — relevance beats volume for grounding. GitHub Spark GitHub Spark lets you build and deploy small full-stack apps from natural-language descriptions , iterating conversationally. You describe what you want; Spark generates the app, and you refine it through prompts. Aimed at quickly turning an idea into a working, deployable app. Lowers the barrier for prototypes, internal tools, and PM/maker use cases. You still review, test, and secure what it produces before relying on it. ✓ Exam Tip Exam cues: curated, shareable context for grounded chat answers → Copilot Spaces ; build a full-stack app from a natural-language de","headings":["Copilot Spaces","GitHub Spark","How they relate to plans"]},{"id":"gh-300/05-enterprise/rest-api-and-management","title":"Management REST API & audit logs","module":"Module 5 · Enterprise Features","url":"gh-300/05-enterprise/rest-api-and-management","text":"At scale, Copilot is administered programmatically. The GH-300 study guide calls out managing subscriptions using the REST API and utilizing audit log events — the tooling admins use to automate seat management and prove governance. Managing subscriptions with the REST API GitHub exposes REST endpoints for Copilot billing and seat management at the organization/enterprise level, so admins can automate what would otherwise be manual clicking: List Copilot seats and see assignment/activity details. Add seats for users or teams (assign licenses). Remove seats for users or teams (reclaim licenses). Read billing information (seat counts, plan). Typical automation: a joiner/leaver workflow that assigns a seat when someone joins a team and reclaims it when they leave, keeping spend aligned with actual usage. ★ Best Practice Automate seat reclamation for inactive users using the seats endpoint (which surfaces last-activity data). It's the simplest lever for controlling Copilot cost without hurting active developers. Audit log events Copilot activity surfaces as audit log events , which admins use for compliance, security investigation, and change tracking . Audit logs answer who changed what, and when for Copilot configuration and access. Track policy changes, seat assignment/removal, and feature enablement. Feed events into your SIEM or review them via the audit log API for oversight. Complement (don't replace) usage/engagement metrics , which measure adoption rather than governance. Need Use Prove who changed a policy or assigned a seat Audit logs Measure adoption / active usage ","headings":["Managing subscriptions with the REST API","Audit log events","Limitations"]},{"id":"gh-300/05-enterprise/security-and-controls","title":"Security & access controls","module":"Module 5 · Enterprise Features","url":"gh-300/05-enterprise/security-and-controls","text":"This page consolidates the security and data-protection controls available to organizations using Copilot — the safeguards that make enterprise adoption defensible. Data protection by plan Business Enterprise : prompts, suggestions, and your code are not used to train the foundation models; code snippets aren't retained for training. Data handling is designed for organizational protection. Individual free tier : fewer guarantees; may allow using data to improve products unless opted out. Pro/Business/Enterprise provide stronger protections. ✓ Exam Tip A clean exam heuristic: if the scenario involves a company protecting its code and needing assurances it won't train public models, the answer is Business or Enterprise (not the free individual tier). Access management Seat/license assignment to users, teams, or organizations. Integration with organization/enterprise membership and, where applicable, SSO/SAML and identity controls at the platform level. Ability to revoke access by unassigning seats. Content exclusions (recap) Admins define files/paths/repos that Copilot must not use as context or send to the service — the primary control for keeping secrets and sensitive code out of prompts and suggestions. Matching-public-code filter (recap) Blocks suggestions that match public code; a prerequisite for IP indemnity on Business/Enterprise and a key control in regulated environments. Auditing monitoring Audit logs for compliance and investigation. Usage metrics / metrics API for oversight and adoption tracking. Defence-in-depth checklist ★ Best Practice Enable content exclusion","headings":["Data protection by plan","Access management","Content exclusions (recap)","Matching-public-code filter (recap)","Auditing monitoring","Defence-in-depth checklist"]},{"id":"gh-300/06-productivity/dotnet","title":".NET 8 & C#","module":"Module 6 · Developer Productivity","url":"gh-300/06-productivity/dotnet","text":"Applied Copilot patterns for the .NET 8 / C# work that dominates your day: APIs, EF Core, DI, minimal APIs, tests, and refactoring. Minimal APIs EF Core Copilot is strong at LINQ-to-EF, but you must watch for N+1 and tracking issues. ★ Best Practice Ask Copilot to project to DTOs and use AsNoTracking() for read paths, and to explain the generated SQL. Verify with logging or a profiler — don't assume the query is optimal. Dependency injection Give Copilot your registration file as context so it wires services the way your app expects (scoped/singleton/transient) and follows your conventions. Unit tests Refactoring to modern C# Use edit mode to modernise: primary constructors, collection expressions, required members, pattern matching. Keep tests green across the change. Common mistakes ⚠ Common Mistake Accepting EF queries that trigger N+1 or load whole tables into memory. Letting Copilot hard-code connection strings/secrets — read from Key Vault /config. Trusting generated tests that assert current behavior rather than intended behavior. ✓ Exam Tip For developer productivity questions, the theme is: Copilot accelerates idiomatic .NET tasks, but you supply context (types, conventions) and validate correctness, performance, and security.","headings":["Minimal APIs","EF Core","Dependency injection","Unit tests","Refactoring to modern C#","Common mistakes"]},{"id":"gh-300/06-productivity/angular","title":"Angular 18","module":"Module 6 · Developer Productivity","url":"gh-300/06-productivity/angular","text":"Copilot works well with modern Angular when you tell it you want standalone components, signals, and typed reactive forms — otherwise it may default to older NgModule-era patterns. Standalone components signals ✓ Exam Tip State the Angular version and the patterns you want ( standalone, signals, new control flow @if/@for ). Without that, Copilot may emit NgModules and *ngIf , reflecting older training data. RxJS reactive forms Copilot is good at operator chains and typed forms — verify subscription cleanup ( takeUntilDestroyed ) and error handling. Routing Angular Material Provide your routes file and a sample Material component as context so generated code matches your setup and design system. Best practices ★ Best Practice Keep a reference component open so Copilot mirrors your structure and imports. Ask for OnPush /signals and proper unsubscription to avoid leaks. Generate Jasmine/Jest specs alongside components and verify DOM assertions. ⚠ Common Mistake Shipping generated components with memory leaks (unmanaged subscriptions) or outdated patterns because the prompt didn't specify Angular 18 conventions.","headings":["Standalone components signals","RxJS reactive forms","Routing Angular Material","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/06-productivity/azure","title":"Azure","module":"Module 6 · Developer Productivity","url":"gh-300/06-productivity/azure","text":"Copilot accelerates Azure development — Functions, Key Vault, Storage, Bicep, App Service — but cloud code needs extra care around secrets, identity, and cost . Azure Functions Key Vault managed identity Steer Copilot toward managed identity and DefaultAzureCredential rather than connection strings or keys. ★ Best Practice Prompt explicitly for managed identity / DefaultAzureCredential and Key Vault references. Reject any suggestion that embeds keys or connection strings in code or config. Bicep / Infrastructure as Code Copilot drafts Bicep for common resources; verify SKUs, regions, naming, and that outputs/parameters match your standards. ⚠ Common Mistake Accepting IaC that opens public access, uses weak TLS, or hard-codes secrets. Generated infra can carry insecure defaults — review every property. App Service configuration Ask for configuration via App Settings / Key Vault references , health checks, and appropriate scaling settings — then confirm against your landing-zone policies. Best practices ★ Best Practice Default to identity-based auth (managed identity) over keys. Keep secrets in Key Vault ; never in code, and never pasted into prompts. Review generated IaC for security defaults (TLS, public access, RBAC) and cost (SKU/tier). Validate region/quota assumptions before deploying. ✓ Exam Tip The Responsible-AI themes reappear in cloud form: generated Azure code isn't pre-secured. You own the review of identity, secret handling, network exposure, and cost.","headings":["Azure Functions","Key Vault managed identity","Bicep / Infrastructure as Code","App Service configuration","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/06-productivity/sql-and-data","title":"SQL Server & data","module":"Module 6 · Developer Productivity","url":"gh-300/06-productivity/sql-and-data","text":"Copilot helps with queries, stored procedures, indexing suggestions, and EF Core mappings — but SQL is where correctness, performance, and injection review matter most. Query authoring optimization ★ Best Practice Ask Copilot to make predicates sargable , to explain the execution plan implications, and to propose indexes — then validate with an actual execution plan. Treat index suggestions as hypotheses to test, not truths. Stored procedures Injection safety ⚠ Common Mistake Accepting dynamic SQL built by string concatenation . It's an injection risk. Prefer parameters; if dynamic SQL is unavoidable, use sp_executesql with parameters and review carefully. EF Core mapping migrations Give Copilot your entity and DbContext so generated configurations and migrations match. Always read migrations before applying — they can drop columns or data if intent is misread. Performance review checklist Sargable predicates; no functions on indexed columns in the WHERE . Right indexes; verify with execution plans, not guesses. Avoid SELECT * ; project needed columns. Watch for implicit conversions and parameter sniffing. ✓ Exam Tip For data tasks, Copilot drafts SQL/EF quickly; you must verify correctness against the schema , performance via plans , and injection safety (parameters over concatenation).","headings":["Query authoring optimization","Stored procedures","Injection safety","EF Core mapping migrations","Performance review checklist"]},{"id":"gh-300/06-productivity/git-and-devops","title":"Git & Azure DevOps","module":"Module 6 · Developer Productivity","url":"gh-300/06-productivity/git-and-devops","text":"Copilot helps across source control and delivery: crafting git commands, resolving merge conflicts, writing commit messages and PR descriptions, and drafting CI/CD pipelines. Git via the CLI Use gh copilot suggest / explain for infrequent or risky operations — always reading the explanation first. ⚠ Common Mistake Running suggested destructive git commands ( reset --hard , force-push) without understanding them. The CLI's confirmation step is your safety check — use it. Merge-conflict assistance In the editor, Copilot Chat can explain both sides of a conflict and propose a resolution. You still verify the merged result compiles and passes tests. Commit messages PRs Copilot can draft commit messages from staged changes. On github.com , it can generate PR summaries (see Module 2). Edit them to capture intent and risk. CI/CD pipelines Copilot drafts GitHub Actions and Azure Pipelines YAML. Verify triggers, secrets handling, permissions, and that steps match your build/test/deploy reality. ★ Best Practice Keep secrets in Actions/Azure DevOps secret stores , never in YAML. Set least-privilege workflow permissions. Review generated pipelines for correct triggers and environment gates before merging. Best practices ★ Best Practice Use Copilot to explain unfamiliar git/pipeline syntax, building your own understanding. Treat generated YAML and commands as drafts to review , especially anything touching secrets, permissions, or deployment. ✓ Exam Tip Across Git/DevOps, the pattern holds: Copilot drafts and explains ; you verify safety (destructive ops, secrets, permissions) and keep ","headings":["Git via the CLI","Merge-conflict assistance","Commit messages PRs","CI/CD pipelines","Best practices"]},{"id":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/prompt-engineering-cheatsheet","title":"Prompt engineering cheat sheet","module":"Module 7 · Cheat Sheets","url":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/prompt-engineering-cheatsheet","text":"A one-page reference. Print-friendly (use the print button). The prompt formula Goal + Context + Constraints + Format Goal — what to produce. Context — relevant types/files (reference, don't paste). Constraints — versions, patterns, security, performance. Format — the exact output shape. Techniques Technique Use when Zero-shot Common, well-understood task Few-shot Output must match a specific style/format Step-by-step Complex logic or debugging Decomposition Large task → smaller reviewed steps Role framing Focused lens (security, performance) Context levers Open the defining files ; keep a reference implementation visible. Reference with #file , #selection , @workspace . Cut noise; relevance beats volume . Put standing rules in custom instructions ; reusable prompts in prompt files . Chat quick reference Kind Examples Slash commands /explain /fix /tests /doc /optimize Participants @workspace @terminal @vscode Variables #file #selection #editor Good vs poor Poor Better fix this guards null order.Lines , add a test make it faster remove N+1; single EF query write tests xUnit: empty, boundary, negative cases ★ Best Practice Front-load the most important constraint, iterate rather than restart, and always read/verify the output.","headings":["The prompt formula","Techniques","Context levers","Chat quick reference","Good vs poor"]},{"id":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/feature-and-plan-comparison","title":"Feature & plan comparison","module":"Module 7 · Cheat Sheets","url":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/feature-and-plan-comparison","text":"Fast reference for the plans and feature domains. Plans Feature Free/Pro Business Enterprise Completions chat Yes (Free limited) Yes Yes Org management policies No Yes Yes Content exclusions No Yes Yes Matching-public-code filter Yes (setting) Yes Yes Code not used to train models Pro: yes Yes Yes IP indemnity (filter on) No Yes Yes Audit logs No Yes Yes Usage metrics / metrics API No Yes Yes github.com integration repo-aware chat No Limited Yes Knowledge bases No No Yes ✓ Exam Tip Business = management + policy + security + indemnity . Enterprise = Business + deep github.com + knowledge bases . Individual = no org admin . Surfaces Surface Highlights Editor (VS/VS Code/JetBrains) Completions, chat, edit agent mode github.com PR summaries, code review, repo-aware chat (Enterprise) CLI ( gh copilot ) suggest , explain (confirm before run) Mobile Chat on the go Modes Mode Use Inline completion Suggestions while typing Chat Explain / ask / local fixes Edit mode Coordinated edits across a known file set Agent mode Autonomous multi-step tasks (you approve) Guidance mechanisms Mechanism Nature Inline prompt One-off request Prompt files ( *.prompt.md ) Reusable task prompts Custom instructions ( .github/copilot-instructions.md ) Always-on conventions","headings":["Plans","Surfaces","Modes","Guidance mechanisms"]},{"id":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/responsible-ai-and-security","title":"Responsible AI & security","module":"Module 7 · Cheat Sheets","url":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/responsible-ai-and-security","text":"Last-minute reference for the Responsible-AI, privacy, and security domains. Core principle Copilot assists; the developer is accountable. Review, test, and validate everything before it ships. Risks mitigations Risk Mitigation Hallucination (confident but wrong) Verify APIs/logic; test Bias/fairness Review naming, examples, assumptions Over-reliance / automation bias Enforce review explainability Insecure code SAST, dependency secret scanning; OWASP review Reproducing public code Enable matching-public-code filter Data leakage Content exclusions ; never paste secrets/PII Prompt injection Treat external content as data, not commands; review agent actions Privacy facts Business/Enterprise : code prompts not used to train models; not retained for training. Content exclusions : control what Copilot may see . Matching filter : controls what Copilot may suggest ; prerequisite for IP indemnity (Business/Enterprise). Individual free tier has weaker guarantees than Pro/Business/Enterprise. Security review checklist Injection (SQL/command/XSS) — parameterise, encode. Secrets — Key Vault / secret stores, never in code or prompts. Identity — managed identity over keys. Access control least privilege. Dependencies — licence + vulnerability review. ✓ Exam Tip On the exam, options featuring human review, validation, content exclusions, the matching filter, or Business/Enterprise data protections are frequently correct for Responsible-AI and privacy scenarios.","headings":["Core principle","Risks mitigations","Privacy facts","Security review checklist"]},{"id":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/exam-day-tips","title":"Exam-day tips","module":"Module 7 · Cheat Sheets","url":"gh-300/08-cheat-sheets/exam-day-tips","text":"Practical strategy for GH-300. Before the exam Confirm the current format, question count, passing score, and objective weightings on the official page. Ensure your environment meets the online-proctoring requirements (ID, quiet room, webcam, stable connection). Do a final pass of the cheat sheets and your weakest domain in the question bank. Time management ~90 minutes; keep a steady pace and don't over-invest in any single item. Flag uncertain questions and return to them. Answer every question — there's no benefit to leaving blanks. Reading questions Watch for select all that apply — multiple correct answers. Note qualifiers: best , most , first , always , never . Eliminate clearly wrong options first, then choose among the rest. Reliable heuristics Human-in-the-loop wins. Options requiring review/validation/testing are usually right for Responsible-AI. Org features = Business/Enterprise. Audit logs, policies, exclusions, metrics, indemnity are not on the individual plan. Knowledge bases = Enterprise. Deep github.com integration = Enterprise. Context is the fix. If Copilot output is generic/wrong, better context/prompt is the usual remedy. Beware absolutes. Copilot guarantees… is typically wrong — it assists, it doesn't guarantee. Common traps ⚠ Common Mistake Choosing an option that removes the human from the loop. Assigning enterprise-admin features to individual plans. Believing Copilot guarantees correctness, security, or originality. Confusing prompt files (reusable prompts) with custom instructions (always-on rules). ★ Best Practice If two options look right, prefe","headings":["Before the exam","Time management","Reading questions","Reliable heuristics","Common traps"]}];
